    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm studying for my accounting exam and I'm stuck on depreciation. Can you explain the formula for straight-line depreciation and give me an example? Let's say a company buys a piece of heavy machinery for $50,000, it has a salvage value of $5,000, and a useful life of 5 years. How would you calculate that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The straight-line depreciation formula is (Cost - Salvage Value) / Useful Life, which calculates a constant expense each year. Using your example, the depreciation amount would be ($50,000 - $5,000) / 5 = $9,000 per year. This means you would record $9,000 in depreciation expense annually until the fifth year. Knowing how to apply this formula helps you understand asset value reduction over time for your tax and financial reports. Good luck with your exam preparation!",
      "source": "target",
